 argues here that slow growth, rampant protectionism, and rising inflation plagued Latin America for years, where corrupt institutions and political unrest undermined the financial outlook of already besieged economies. Tracing Latin America’s growth and decline through two centuries, this volume illustrates how a once-prosperous continent now lags behind. Of interest to scholars and policymakers alike, it offers new insight into the relationship between political systems and economic development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLatin America -- Economic conditions. 0aLatin America -- Economic policy. 0aLatin America -- History. 0aLatin America -- Politics and government. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  alatin america, mexico, argentina, chile, politics, government, history, economics, unrest, revolution, corruption, inflation, protectionism, growth, textiles, industry, nonfiction, stablization, foreign advisors, currency, lending, governance, solvency, risk, emerging markets, debt, inequality, wealth, poverty, portugal, taxation.1 aBordo, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatão, Luis A. V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Sebastian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEscosura, Leandro Prados de la, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsquivel, Gerardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsquivel, Gerardo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrandes, Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGómez-Galvarriato, Aurora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel